title: Add ability for pre-packed weights of shared initializers to be shared across sessions
body:
**Description**: The concept of shared initializers was introduced so as to have memory footprint savings when there are scenarios where-in the same weight(s) are shared across multiple models. These weights needn't be duplicated in memory and this was the motivation for shared initializers. With pre-packing, some weights are pre-processed at model load time and now the "pre-packed" versions of shared initializers are duplicated in memory because pre-packed buffers are owned by individual kernels, thus removing all the goodness of shared initializers in the first place. This change attempts to provide infrastructure to have pre-packed weights of shared initializers to be shared between sessions and thereby preserve the memory savings offered by shared initializers. 

**Motivation and Context**
Required by an internal team

title: Discrepencies between onnxruntime and numpy with operator Einsum
body:
**Describe the bug**
numpy and onnxruntime disagree for operator `Einsum('abc,cd,def->abd', ...)`.

**System information**
- OS Platform and Distribution (e.g., Linux Ubuntu 16.04): all
- ONNX Runtime installed from (source or binary): master branch
- ONNX Runtime version:
- Python version: 3.8
- Visual Studio version (if applicable):
- GCC/Compiler version (if compiling from source):
- CUDA/cuDNN version:
- GPU model and memory:

**To Reproduce**

```
import onnx
from onnx import helper, numpy_helper
import numpy as np
from onnxruntime import InferenceSession

def make_model(equation):
    model = helper.make_model(
        opset_imports=[helper.make_operatorsetid('', 13)],
        ir_version=6,
        producer_name='einsum_test',
        producer_version='1.6.0',
        graph=helper.make_graph(
            name='einsum_test',
            inputs=[helper.make_tensor_value_info("X", onnx.TensorProto.FLOAT, None),
                    helper.make_tensor_value_info("Y", onnx.TensorProto.FLOAT, None),
                    helper.make_tensor_value_info("Z", onnx.TensorProto.FLOAT, None)],
            outputs=[helper.make_tensor_value_info("A", onnx.TensorProto.FLOAT, None)],
            nodes=[
                helper.make_node("Einsum", ["X", "Y", "Z"], ["A"],
                                 equation=equation)
            ]
        )
    )
    return model

equation = "abc,cd,def->abd"
model = make_model(equation)

X = np.arange(0, 8).reshape((2, 2, 2)).astype(np.float32)
Y = np.arange(0, 4).reshape((2, 2)).astype(np.float32)
Z = np.arange(0, 8).reshape((2, 2, 2)).astype(np.float32)
np_out = np.einsum(equation, X, Y, Z)
print("numpy\n", np_out)

sess = InferenceSession(model.SerializeToString())
ort_out = sess.run(None, {'X': X, 'Y': Y, 'Z': Z})
print("onnxruntime\n", ort_out[0])
```
Current output:
```
numpy
 [[[ 12.  66.]
  [ 36. 242.]]

 [[ 60. 418.]
  [ 84. 594.]]]

onnxruntime
 [[[  2.  15.]
  [  6.  55.]]

 [[ 10.  95.]
  [ 14. 135.]]]
```

See PR #7374, unit tests catching this issue is already implemented.

**Expected behavior**
numpy and onnxruntime should have the same output.

title: Fix Microsoft.AI.MachineLearning .NET5 publishing and C# Store Release build
body:
There are 2 fixes in this change.

Issue #1: The Microsoft.AI.MachineLearning package does not publish native binaries to the package output directory automatically.  

Reason: This regressed when all of the nuget payload was moved into folders with non-canonical names. This was done to prevent nuget from performing automatic copies, as its logic was getting confused when multiple binaries are produced for the same TFM (static, dynamic crt for native binaries). After moving the files to non-canonical names, all project configuration is now performed by the package itself by including its own targets/props files in the build directory. The copy that was added into the targets file only copied out to the bin directory and not the publish directory, causing the regression.

Fix: The Fix is to call ReferenceCopyLocalPaths on the intended binaries, and that will configure the project to binplace and publish the native binaries.


Issue #2: C# UWP Applications cannot build release because Microsoft.AI.MachineLearning.Experimental.winmd references Windows.AI.MachineLearning.winmd.

Reason: This happened because the core Windows AI API is implemented in a single file Windows.AI.MachineLEarning.idl, and shared between the Inbox implementation and the Redist. However, dependent idls fail to work when referencing Windows.AI.MachineLearning.idl, as import statements are interpretted as winmd references. This causes Release builds to fail, as there is no Windows.AI.MachineLearning.winmd packaged in the redist package.

Fix: The fix is to copy the idls into a separate folder at build, and rename them to Microsoft.* files so that midlrt does not add erroneous winmd references.

title: "Sticky" allocation of worker threads
body:
**Description**: This change updates the heuristics used when a thread selects which worker threads to push work to on entering a parallel loop.  Previously, worker threads would maintain a best-effort bitmap of "good worker hints" indicating the threads that were likely to be spinning waiting for work.  This change uses a simpler heuristic where a thread records which workers ran its previous loop, and then re-submits its next loop to those same workers.  The aim is to retain affinity between a thread and a set of workers, and to avoid maintaining the "good worker hints" bitmaps.  

**Motivation and Context**: Profiling suggested that maintaining the "good worker hints" was taking unexpected time, particularly on NUMA systems.  In addition, when running many concurrent workloads, the hints did not provide a way to help retain locality of workers and hence data in caches.  Testing to confirm no regressions on microbenchmark (./build/Linux/Release/onnxruntime_benchmark --benchmark_filter=BM_ThreadPoolParallelFor) and on Linux mobilenet_v1_1.0_224.onnx, comparing p50 and p99 with vs without this change:

1 concurrent:
p50 0.0172s vs 0.0181s
p99 0.0204s vs 0.0216s

2 concurrent:
p50 0.0172s vs 0.0181s
p99 0.0213s vs 0.0221s

title: Resize Operator rounds-down instead of round-to-even for int32/uint8

labels.name: component:operator
labels.description: related to specific ONNX operator support

body:
**Describe the bug**
As mentioned on https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/pull/7216 I noticed that the resize implementation in ORT _casts_ interpolated values to the destination type instead of rounding. That is, with the current implementation, trying to linearly interpolate to 6 elements between 1 and 2 with an integral destination type will lead to a result of `1 1 1 1 1 2` instead of `1 1 1 2 2 2`. This behavior becomes more pathological (and further from the floating point version) the more values you try to interpolate between two close numbers.

I opened an [issue](https://github.com/onnx/onnx/issues/3390) in the ONNX repo to clarify the intended behavior which is missing from the spec, but given that almost all other onnx operators use round-to-even mode I suspect that the current implementation in ORT is a bug.

Changing the current implementation for `uint8/int32` would be a breaking change however.

**Urgency**
P2 urgency; we need this behavior clarified so that we can run a quantized mask-rcnn model.

title: Add support to **kwargs in ORTModule forward() method
body:
ORTModule currently supports:
* positionals (e.g. `def forward(self, pos0, pos1, ...)`
* positionals + variable positions (e.g. `def forward(self, pos0, pos1, ..., *args)`
* positionals + keywords (e.g. `def forward(self, pos0, pos1, ..., kw0=None, kw1=None, ...)`

ORTModule currently DOES NOT support:
* Mixing variable positionals with keywords (e.g. `def forward(self, *args, kw0=None, kw1=None, ...)`
* Variable keywords (e.g. `def forward(self, ..., **kwargs)`

In this PR, support to `**kwargs` will be added, which will also support mixing `*args` with keywords

Currently, we rely on PyTorch ONNX exporter to flatten the input from (positionals, variable positionals and keywords) into a single sequential tuple of tensors. This PR will flatten the input before exporting the model. That allow us to support the aforementioned scenarios without changing the exporter, which is a third party component. A future PR will propose these changes to PyTorch

title: Expose flag in PyBind API for tensor memory re-use in allocation planner.
body: Memory re-use in memory planning allows to reuse tensor buffer between tensors of non-overlapping life cycles if they are of the same size. The intent behind this policy was to minimize allocation calls made into the heap/allocator, however, this policy can lead to memory being held for longer than needed and can impact peak memory consumption while calls made into the heap/allocator are usually cheap. This was observed in ORTModule experiments, hence, this change also turns-off memory reuse in ORTModule.

title: Problem with  symbolic shape inference for "Squeeze"

labels.name: component:operator
labels.description: related to specific ONNX operator support

body:
For the Squeeze operation the shape-inference ins not working properly ***if no axes are provided***. In this case all the dimensions equal to 1 should be removed from the input-shape (see: [Squeeze](https://github.com/onnx/onnx/blob/master/docs/Operators.md#squeeze)), but currently all dimensions are removed by shape-inference, ndepended of there value. This is due to a bug in the â€˜non-symbolicâ€™ shape inference called in _onnx_infer_single_node(â€¦) not working properly in this case.
I already tried a fix (see below), but wasn't able to set up a corresponding pull request.
If someone could look into that or tell me how to set up permissions correctly so that I can create a pr.

Thanks

Sugessted fix:
```python

    def _infer_Squeeze(self, node): 
        input_shape = self._get_shape(node, 0)

        # Depending on op-version 'axes' are provided as attribute or via 2nd input      
        axes = get_attribute(node, 'axes')
        if axes is None:
            axes = self._try_get_value(node, 1)

        if axes == None:
            output_shape = [s for s in input_shape if s != 1]
        else:
            axes = [handle_negative_axis(a, len(input_shape)) for a in axes]
            output_shape = []
            for i in range(len(input_shape)):
                if i not in axes:
                    output_shape.append(input_shape[i])

        vi = self.known_vi_[node.output[0]]
        vi.CopyFrom(
            helper.make_tensor_value_info(node.output[0], self.known_vi_[node.input[0]].type.tensor_type.elem_type,
                                          output_shape))
        self._pass_on_sympy_data(node)
```

title: Fix RoiAlign CPU EP issues
body: **Description**: (1) 0 size regions are valid and should be treated as sampled points, not forced to 1. This leads to test failures when sampling tiny points or slivers in our ONNX conformance tests. `bin_size_w` and `bin_size_h` are only multiplied anyway, not divided, and so an attempt to prevent division by zero (or whatever the original intention) is unnecessary. (2) max mode should take the *entire* bilinear sample, not a fragment of it. This line `output_val = std::max(output_val, val);` is sufficient, while the other `max` calls are wrong. (3) defer this until after ONNX adds a compat attribute in https://github.com/onnx/onnx/pull/3625 input pixel alignment is 0.5 off - the correct equation is `(x + 0.5) * scale - 0.5`, but the final 0.5 was missed `(x + 0.5) * scale` (see https://arxiv.org/abs/1703.06870). **Motivation and Context** - _Why is this change required? What problem does it solve?_ The DML/WinML ONNX conformance tests fail on CPU for a number of cases. - _If it fixes an open issue, please link to the issue here._ https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/6921 (also related https://github.com/onnx/onnx/issues/3428)

title: ROCM reduction performance issue for BERT performance optimization
body:
**Description**:
Use `reduce_sum()` when computing a full reduction to scalar (in-shape=[N], out-shape[1]) in loss-related kernels, rather than cuDNN or MIOpen.

**Motivation and Context**
There's a performance optimization in NVidia BERT implementation to select out non-zero entries in a particular output tensor:
https://github.com/mlperf/training_results_v0.7/blob/master/NVIDIA/benchmarks/bert/implementations/pytorch/modeling.py#L697-L698

This causes the tensor shape to vary on each batch.  This tensor is also used in a reduction.  In MIOpen, it dynamically generates and compiles a reduction kernel for each shape/datatype/etc.:
https://github.com/ROCmSoftwarePlatform/MIOpen/blob/1673b9f0ff6148f1972080240a70c73b5915ff0b/src/reducetensor.cpp#L485-L553

This causes noticeable slowdowns (~2s per kernel generation).  To workaround this, we can use the built-in `reduce_sum()` for special cases like reduce-all to scalar.  This reduction kernel is already heavily optimized for this case, so there's no performance issue.

body:
# **Overview:**
Implements partial graph execution feature to enable ORTModule coordination with PyTorch using a _single_ thread instead of _two_ threads as in the current master. Allows a sub-graph to be executed in a _PartialRun_ call which returns the state of the graph in addition to fetches. The state essentially holds on to intermediate tensors. Keeping the state around keeps things performant by avoiding exchanging intermediate tensors back and forth between subsequent partial graph run calls that can add significant overhead. It also simplifies the design.

Supersedes https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/pull/7077 by keeping stuff stateless inside ONNX Runtime.

# **Block diagram:**

![partial_graph_execution-7](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/1211949/116354311-147f4d00-a7ad-11eb-996b-e029388e94fc.png)


## **ORTModule:**
The python front-end for ONNX Runtime Training. It creates an ORT session that represents an ONNX graph to train on. Then using RunForward and RunBackward calls the training is conducted. A pair of RunForward and RunBackward calls is represented by a state called RunCtx, this state also contains PartialGraphExecutionState that captures the state of the graph after a partial graph run in ORT. Using this state the graph execution can be resumed. This state is essentially a list of intermediate tensors that are produced during a graph run. 

## **Training Agent:**
This acts as the proxy to C++ backend of ORT. It is a C++ layer that interacts with ORTModule using pybind. 

## **Inference Session:**
This is the entry point into ORT backend. It contains the PartialRun call that partially runs through a graph using a list of feeds and returns a list of fetches (if any). It invokes Partial Executor that either initializes or updates an existing Partial Graph Execution state with Execution Frame that contains list of intermediate tensors. 


# **Performance benefits:**
We are seeing **2.73% speed/throughput improvements** using partial graph execution change over master on zcode model.

In the below graph after running for 4.6K steps the throughput is as following:

1. Magenta line is PyTorch baseline: **3.197e+4**
2. Grey line is master from 04/15 with symbolic fix: **3.1979e+4**
3. Teal line is the same master commit from 04/15 + symbolic fix + partial graph execution change: **3.2863e+4**

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/1211949/115932756-6a1cc800-a442-11eb-8939-1fb748c60dcd.png)

title: Add batch interface to floating point GEMM
body:
**Description**: Add batch interface to single and double precision floating point GEMM functions.

**Motivation and Context**
Currently in high dimension matmul, we call multiple GEMM sequentially. Now we execute these GEMMs in parallel, removing barriers between two adjacent GEMM operations.


Performance tested with Bert and T5 model. Bert model shows no noticeable perf differences, as the heavy lifting is done by the attention operator, which is not changed in this PR. In T5 model, we see no regression on low parallel threads (x4), and performance improvement is more pronounced in high number of threads (8-16). T5 shows 10% speedup with 16 threads. With profiling, we can see the most expensive MatMul operators in T5 achieves around 20% speedup with 16 threads.

title: Access violation when using TensorRT ExecutionProvider on multiple GPU
body:
**Describe the bug**
Access violation error being thrown during the engine building phase when using TensorRT ExecutionProvider on multiple GPU.

**Urgency**
URGENT. We were expecting to ship TensorRT support in QAS in April, but it is now blocked by this issue since we have multi-GPU machines at production, which would be impacted by this issue.

**System information**
- OS Platform and Distribution (e.g., Linux Ubuntu 16.04): Windows Server 2019 Datacenter
- ONNX Runtime installed from (source or binary): source
- ONNX Runtime version: master (4971310d6aaf90452a72856670db4b5e6b74e0e6)

- GPU model and memory:V100/32G (the machine has 8 V100 GPUs.)

**To Reproduce**
- Describe steps/code to reproduce the behavior.
1. Load the same model to all the 8 GPUs (via 8 separate sessions).
2. Execute the model in parallel for all the 8 sessions at the same time.
Access violation error being thrown when building engine from this line: https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/8d737f977056444a307f1b7f0bcd402fba62d790/onnxruntime/core/providers/tensorrt/tensorrt_execution_provider.cc#L1507

However, if I send the initial request (which triggers engine building) to each GPU sequentially, then no exception happens.
